    "We modify the usual proof of the discrete convolution theorem to use Z/pZ instead of C.NTT(v * w) i = n-1 k ’Ż½ ’ŻŁ n-1 j=0 v j ŌĆó w k-j ’ŻČ ’ŻĖ Žē ik (47) = n-1 j=0 v j Žē ij n-1 k=0 w k-j Žē i(k-j) (48) = ’Ż½ ’ŻŁ n-1 j=0 v j Žē ij ’ŻČ ’ŻĖ n-1 t=0 w t Žē it Let t = k -j (49) = NTT(v) i ŌĆó NTT(w) i(50)The convolution theorem allows for the implementation of convolution in O(n log n) time using the NTT (or FFT), rather than the naive method requiring O(n 2).",
    "This efficiency improvement makes randomness extraction feasible for input lengths n > 10 6, as shown in Section 2.3 \"Performance\".",
    "A.3 Proofs for the Circulant extractorTo prove that our Circulant construction is an extractor with the parameters in Section 4, we first show that the family of functions derived from circulant matrices forms a two-universal hash family.",
    "With this established, we apply the Leftover Hashing Lemma [60] and Corollary 5.6.1 of [19] to conclude that the construction is quantum-proof.",
    "The main difficulty in proving the two-universality of the Circulant extractor comes from certain 'problematic' input pairs (those differing in every position)."
